{
  "verdict": "reject",
  "conceptual_groups": [
    {
      "id": "group-1",
      "summary": "Artifact contract and lifecycle are internally inconsistent, so the package cannot prove what is canonical, what is run-scoped, and what completion actually requires.",
      "severity": "blocking",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f1",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "The canonical role artifacts are not referenced with their required tool-rooted paths in <outputs>. The supplied self-check already reports the four required canonical outputs as missing there, which means the package fails its own output contract.",
          "source_section": "<outputs>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f2",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "Step 5 says decision log, board summary, and result artifacts are always written, but <outputs> models only basename-style canonical artifacts plus conditional evidence artifacts. The draft never cleanly states where non-frozen decision-log and board-summary copies live versus promoted canonical files.",
          "source_section": "<steps> Step 5; <outputs>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f3",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "<completion> says the workflow is complete when all applicable artifacts are written and 'Decision log updated (on freeze)', but the numbered flow says decision logging and board summary production happen for every run. That leaves non-frozen terminal states under-specified.",
          "source_section": "<completion>; <steps> Step 5"
        },
        {
          "id": "f4",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The contract summary exposes package_files only as basenames, while the actual required outputs are tool-relative canonical paths. Without a single declared source of truth, promotion targets are ambiguous.",
          "source_section": "Contract summary.package_files; <outputs>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Make canonical promotion targets explicit and singular. Define the exact canonical paths in the package contract, mirror those same paths in <outputs>, and separately define run-scoped evidence paths for all terminal states. Then align <completion> to that lifecycle so frozen and non-frozen runs are both mechanically complete."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-2",
      "summary": "Authority and governance sources are not modeled consistently with project governance, which blurs who actually governs the role and where runtime rules come from.",
      "severity": "major",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f5",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "<authority> makes the role 'Subordinate to' static docs, but bootstrap and architecture state that the COO controller governs turns and runtime rules come from the memory engine. This draft shifts operative authority toward documents instead of treating them as governing references or evidence.",
          "source_section": "<authority>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The draft says it owns board-review orchestration while also excluding application runtime orchestration, but it does not crisply distinguish board-local review execution from broader system runtime authority. The boundary is implied, not contract-clear.",
          "source_section": "<authority>; <scope>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f7",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Freeze authority is split across <role>, <guardrails>, and Step 4 without a single normative freeze predicate tied to the contract. The statements are directionally aligned, but not encoded as one authoritative rule surface.",
          "source_section": "<role>; <guardrails>; <steps> Step 4; Contract summary.governance"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Anchor operative authority to the COO-controlled runtime contract, with memory-engine rules as runtime source of truth and docs as references. Then define board-review orchestration as a bounded exception inside that authority model, and express one freeze predicate once in the contract and mirror it verbatim in markdown."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-3",
      "summary": "Scope text is structurally noisy and duplicates exclusions, which weakens coherence and makes literal validation more brittle than necessary.",
      "severity": "minor",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f8",
          "severity": "minor",
          "description": "The Not in scope list repeats 'Application workflow creation' and 'Application runtime orchestration' with slightly different wording. That is not fatal, but it creates avoidable ambiguity.",
          "source_section": "<scope>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f9",
          "severity": "minor",
          "description": "Because exclusions are duplicated and paraphrased, the scope surface is harder to validate mechanically against contract text and more likely to trigger false structural mismatches.",
          "source_section": "<scope>; <steps> Step 3"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Collapse each exclusion into one canonical sentence and keep the markdown wording identical to the contract out-of-scope strings where machine validation depends on literal matching."
    }
  ],
  "residual_risks": [
    "Even after path and lifecycle fixes, reviewer identity terms such as 'Codex' and 'Claude' still need schema-level normalization to stay machine-auditable across providers and models.",
    "The self-check remains brittle if it depends on literal string and path matching without an explicit false-positive or semantic-equivalence policy."
  ],
  "strengths": [
    "All required top-level tags are present and the overall role shape is easy to follow.",
    "The draft keeps the role focused on governed role-package creation rather than drifting into tool creation or code execution.",
    "The guardrails correctly reject invented semantics, authority expansion, and freezing with unresolved material pushback.",
    "The workflow is organized into a sensible validate-draft-self-check-review-promote sequence."
  ]
}

